  <h1>What Should I Eat for Dinner Today? (The Asian Version)</h1>

  <p>
    Have you ever needed dinner ideas to see what you’re in the mood for, and
    decided to search online?
  </p>

  <p>
    That is me pretty much all the time. I search up what to eat for dinner and
    look at 5 different pages on Google.
  </p>

  <p>
    And honestly, it’s not helpful to me at all because I am Asian. I have mostly
    Asian ingredients at home and when I eat out, I want some sort of Asian food
    most of the time. But these lists usually have things like 20 different pastas
    or meat dishes that I have never craved before. These lists are too Western
    for me. So my search for dinner ideas sadly comes to an end with no fruitful
    result.
  </p>

  <p>
    If you’re like me, I’ve got your back. I made a mega-list of Asian foods to
    increase your appetite and inspire your dinner choices! Check it out:
  </p>

  <div class="divider">• • •</div>

  <h2>Korean Foods</h2>

  <ol>
    <li>Bibimbap (mixed rice with vegetables and beef)</li>
    <li>Bulgogi (marinated beef barbecue)</li>
    <li>Galbijjim (soy sauce braised short ribs)</li>
    <li>Gimbap (seaweed rice rolls)</li>
    <li>Samgyeopsal (grilled pork belly)</li>
    <li>Galbi (marinated grilled ribs)</li>
    <li>Sundubu-jjigae (soft tofu stew)</li>
    <li>Doenjang-jjigae (soybean paste stew)</li>
    <li>Mandu (dumplings)</li>
    <li>Naengmyeon (cold buckwheat noodles)</li>
    <li>Jajangmyeon (noodles in black bean sauce)</li>
    <li>Bossam (boiled pork wrap)</li>
    <li>Galbitang (short rib soup)</li>
    <li>Yukgaejang (spicy beef soup)</li>
    <li>Gamjatang (spicy pork bone stew)</li>
    <li>Budae-jjigae (army stew)</li>
    <li>Seolleongtang (ox bone soup)</li>
    <li>Kimchi-jjigae (kimchi stew)</li>
    <li>Janchi Guksu (banquet noodles)</li>
    <li>Dakdoritang (spicy chicken stew)</li>
  </ol>

